title: Step3
tags:
---
//Element 11
Now take the Nichrome wire that we also call the test wire and dip it in the first beaker containing Potassium Chloride. #line:16

//Element 12
Hold the end of the test wire into the flame, and observe how the flame changes color. #line:17

//Element 13
The flame should present a lilac color. A lilac color appears in the flame when Potassium ions are present. #line:18



//Element 14
Before testing the next solution, we must remove all the potassium chloride from the test wire. #line:19

//Element 15
To do this, hold the end of the wire into the flame until it glows orange. #line:20
//Then remove the test wire from the flame and allow to cool for 7 seconds. #line:21



//Element 16
Now dip the wire into the second beaker containing Lithium Chloride and repeat the test.  #line:22

//Element 17
A crimson color appears in the flame when Lithium ions are present. Remember to clean the Nichrome wire once you're done.  #line:23



//Element 18
Now dip the wire into the third beaker containing Calcium Chloride and repeat the test.  #line:24

//Element 19
A red-orange color appears in the flame when Calcium ions are present.<br><br>Once again clean the Nichrome wire by holding in the flame.  #line:25




//Element 20
Now dip the wire into the fouth beaker containing Copper Chloride and repeat the test.  #line:25a

//Element 21
A green color appears in the flame when Copper ions are present.<br><br>Don't forget to clean the Nichrome wire once you're done.  #line:26




//Element 22
Finally, dip the wire into the fifth beaker containing Sodium Chloride and repeat the test.  #line:26a

//Element 23
An orange color appears in the flame when Sodium ions are present. <br><br>Clean the Nichrome wire one last time.  #line:27



//Element 24
Congratulations on reaching the end of the experiment. Proceed to the test section if you're comfortable or replay the experience. #line:28
